properties.Name: Green Mountain Pumpback (A.K.A Blue River)
properties.Prj_Propos: Denver Water and the Colorado River Water Conservation District
properties.Source: Denver Post & Colorado Water Conservation Board
properties.Prj_Status: This project has been an idea since the 1980's but hasn't moved forward much since then.  In 2007 a federal  feasibility study was completed. The idea  is to take downstream water from Silverthorne and Heeney, and pump it uphill to Dillon, where Denver can then integrate it into its water supply system.

properties.Name: Moffat Firming Project
properties.Prj_Status: This project is an expansion of an existing dam. The  Environmental Impact Statement is expected in 2014, and then after it is released the  U.S Army Corps of Engineers will make a decision on whether or not to allow the project to move forward. If this happens, construction is expected to take four years.

properties.Name: Windy Gap Firming Project
properties.Prj_Propos: Northern Water Municipal Sub district: Windy Gap
properties.Recipients: 10 Front Range municipalities, two water districts, one power provider
properties.Prj_Status: The U.S. Bureau of Reclamation released the project's Final Environmental Impact Statement in 2011. The Bureau of Reclamation is expected to release a final decision in 2013. Other  required approvals are also anticipated in 2013. If all paperwork is approved, construction could begin and it is estimated that it would take five years to complete the project.

properties.Name: Yampa Pumpback Project (A.K.A Maybell)
properties.Recipients: Front Range residents. The Front Range is an area east of the Rocky Mountains that extends north and south of Denver
properties.Source: Friends of the Yampa & Colorado River Water Conservation District (CRWCD)
properties.Prj_Status: After conceptual plans were introduced in 2006, the project stalled in 2008 when officials at the Northern Colorado Water Conservancy District announced that they would not pursue the project. The Yampa is one of the last  wild and free rivers in the West.

properties.Name: Flaming Gorge Pipeline
properties.Prj_Propos: Developer Aaron Million or South Denver Metro water providers
properties.Recipients: Front Range residents. The Front Range is an area east of the Rocky Mountains that extends north and south of Denver.
properties.Prj_Status: The project has been denied by multiple agencies and lacks financial support necessary to move forward.

properties.Name: Blue Mesa Pumpback (A.K.A. Gunnison)
properties.Recipients: Front Range residents. The Front Range is an area east of the Rocky Mountains that extends north and south of Denver.
properties.Prj_Status: This project proposal to pump water from Blue Mesa Reservoir to Antero Reservoir is in the early conceptual stages. Barriers to this project include the fact that new water rights would need to be established, and that it would cost upwards of $225 million per year to operate.

properties.Name: Big Chino Ranch
properties.Recipients: City of Prescott, Town of Prescott Valley
properties.Prj_Status: The project is on hold indefinitely. Originally Prescott and Prescott Valley planned to have the project operating by 2009 but  due to lack of demand for the water the project is now uncertain.  Additionally, residents would have to vote to approved the project.  Groundwater testing ongoing since 2010.

properties.Name: Navajo-Gallup Projects
properties.Recipients: 43 Navajo chapters, Town of Gallup and Jicarilla Apache Nation
properties.Source: U.S. Department of Interior & the Bureau of Reclamation
properties.Prj_Status: Under Construction - Construction began in June 2012. The entire project is estimated to take between 10 and 12 years to complete.

properties.Name: Lake Powell Pipeline
properties.Prj_Status: In February 213 state water resource officials acknowledged a delayed need for the project based on revised projections in Washington County population growth.

properties.Name: Gila River Diversion
properties.Prj_Status: The State of New Mexico has until 2014 to decide how to use the water they were guaranteed in an amendment to the 2004 Arizona Water Settlements Act.  Now a state appointed commission has the power to decide which water projects to fund.  Political pressure to fund a  project to withdraw water from the Gila and deliver it to either Deming, NM or Las Cruces, NM or another location is building because a big infrastructure project would get federal funding.
